</div><div id="c471">

<p>Anybody can say they&#8217;re Atrios, but can anyone post an article on Atrios&#8217;s website?  In this world of dumpster-diving and identity theft, a pseudonym can be just as secure as a real-life name - perhaps even more so.  &#8220;Atrios&#8221; is more of a brand than an identity.  I don&#8217;t know or care what the person&#8217;s real-life name is, or even if it&#8217;s a group effort.  What I do care about is that when I see the name &#8220;Atrios&#8221; on an article I can associate it with other things that have appeared under that name and have some idea what I&#8217;m getting.  That&#8217;s a critical difference between anonymity and pseudonymity; methinks some folks need to read Brin&#8217;s &#8220;Transparent Society&#8221; to understand more.</p>

